es from cannolis to spinach and feta pretzels most stores sell books magazines newspapers dvds graphic novels gifts games toys music and nook e‑readers and tablets contents  history  –  –  s  s–s  s  s  publishing  food service  community involvement  barnes  noble nook  college bookstores  see also  references  further reading  external links historyedit clifford noble in  –edit barnes  noble originated in  with a bookstore called john barnes  company located in the cooper union building in new york city in the fall of  gilbert clifford noble a thenrecent harvard graduate from westfield massachusetts was hired to work there as a clerk in  noble was made a partner and the name of the shop was changed to hinds  noble in  hinds  noble moved to – w th street in  noble bought out hinds and entered into a partnership with william barnes son of his old friend charles the name of the store was changed to barnes  noble charles barnes had opened a bookprinting business in wheaton illinois in  william barnes divested himself of his ownership interest in his fathers firm just before his partnership with noble and it would go on to become follett corporation although the flagship store once featured the motto founded in  the c m barneswilcox company never had any connection to barnes  noble other than the fact that both were partly owned at different times by william barnes –edit in  noble sold his share of the company to william barnes son john wilcox barnes noble died on june   at the age of  barnes  nobles former flagship store at  fifth avenue in manhattan new york that operated from  to  in  at the height of the great depression the bookstore moved to a flagship location on th street and fifth avenue which served as so until its closure in  the noble family retained ownership of an associated publishing business and barnes  noble opened a new publishing division in  in  the store was one of the first businesses to feature muzak it underwent a major renovation the following year that decade the company opened stores in brooklyn and chicago william barnes died in  at the age of  and his son john wilcox barnes assumed full control the company underwent a significant expansion between the s and the s opening an additional retail store on rd street in manhattan as well as shops near the city university of new york harvard and other northeast college campuses john barnes died in  and the company was sold to the conglomerate amtel two years later barnes and noble corporate headquarters  – fifth avenue between west th and th streets in the flatiron district neighborhood of manhattan new york city th avenue store sign sedit the business was purchased in  by leonard riggio for  million by then it had been badly mismanaged over the prior two years and consisted only of a significantly reduced wholesale operation and a single retail location—the store at  fifth avenue in  barnes  noble became the first bookstore chain to advertise on television and a year later the company became the first bookseller in america to discount books by selling the new york times bestselling titles at  off the publishers list price between the s and the s barnes  noble opened smaller discount stores which eventually phased out in favor of larger stores they also began to publish their own books to be sold to mailorder customers these titles were primarily affordable reissues of outofprint titles and selling them through mailorder catalogs allowed barnes  noble to reach new customers nationwide in november  in response to a question from a member of the studio audience the british twin brothers norris mcwhirter and ross mcwhirter who were editors of the britishproduced guinness book of records claimed on the bbc one television programme record breakers that the fifth avenue store of barnes and noble had overtaken that of londons foyles bookshop to become the worlds biggest bookstore s–sedit barnes  noble continued to expand throughout the s and it purchased the primarily shopping mallbased b dalton chain from dayton hudson in  for an estimated  million to  million the last b dalton stores were scheduled to close in january  in  barnes and noble had purchased the store chain bookstop solveig robinson author of the book in society an introduction to print culture wrote that the purchase gave barnes and noble the necessary knowhow and infrastructure to create what in  became the definitive bookselling superstore the acquisition of the  b dalton bookstores turned the company into a nationwide retailer and by the end of fiscal year  the secondlargest online bookseller in the united states bns critics claim that it has contributed to the decline of local and independent booksellers before barnes  noble created its official website it sold books directly to customers through mailorder catalogs it first began selling books online through an early videotex service called trintex a joint venture between sears and ibm but the companys website was not launched until may  according to bns website it now carries over  million titles sedit in  leonard riggios brother stephen riggio was named barnes  nobles ceo a position he held until  the barnes  noble review an online literary site was launched in october  it featured book reviews columns and interview from critics and authors such as michael dirda john freeman ac grayling ezra klein paul lafarge mark sarvas dava sobel neal stephenson stephen king and greil marcus music critic robert christgau has also written essays for the site video games and related items were sold in the companys gamestop retail outlets from  until late  when the division was spun off by distributing its  stake in gamestop to stakeholders of barnes  nobles making it an independent company sedit website president william lynch was named ceo in  he is credited with helping launch the companys electronic book store and overseeing the introduction of its electronic book reader the nook many observers saw his appointment as 